Some patients with new coronary pneumonia are not very dangerous at the early stage, but the later stage will suddenly accelerate, the patient will soon enter a state of multiple organ failure, will be an inflammatory storm

Patients with mild illness should not be taken lightly

This article was adapted from the Southern People's weekly

By Yang Nan, southern people weekly

He Peiyun, Nie Yangxin, Intern Reporter, southern people weekly

Figure | provided by Sun Yat-sen Hospital affiliated to Fudan University

Editor | Kuai Lehao Zhou Jianping

On that day, Zhong Ming, deputy director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Shanghai Zhongshan Hospital, received instructions from the National Health Commission to go to Wuhan to participate in the rescue of critically ill patients with new pneumonia. He was the first Shanghai medical expert to come to Wuhan's aid. It was only an hour from the time he received the assignment to the time he set out.

That night, he and two other experts from Guangzhou and Hangzhou arrived in Macheng on a high-speed railway. They were then driven to Wuhan by the Hubei Provincial Health Commission. Via A high-speed toll booth, the three experts switched to a car with access to the city before arriving at the hotel. On January 24, Zhong Ming entered the Jinyintan Hospital in Wuhan to start work. Golden Pool is the first group of fixed-point Admission Hospital in Wuhan, Wuhan new pneumonia critically ill patients is one of the main choices.

The following is an exclusive interview with Dr. Zhong Ming with southern people weekly last night.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On New Year's Eve, Zhong Ming rode the high-speed railway to assist Wuhan

Southern People Weekly: What's your main job after you arrive at the gold and Silver Lake?

Zhong Ming: At that time, there were three members of the medical treatment expert group in the gold and Silver Pool, and then we were sent to complete the clinical work of the first line.

The intensive care unit (ICU) on their south seventh floor has only sixteen beds, but patients far exceed this load. The hospital was going to open two floors below and convert the general ward into a temporary ICU. So two days before we got there, the I.C.U. had just moved the equipment in. I was placed on the sixth floor, the main battlefield with the largest number of critically ill patients. I led a temporary treatment team of doctors and nurses from all over Hubei Province who came to Wuhan for assistance. They treated half of the critically ill patients in the ward at that time, about 16. My team consisted of three ICU doctors, supported from all over Hubei Province, three non-ICU doctors from the hospital, and some nurses.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the empty high-speed train, Dr. Zhong Ming said, "the family is really worried, but they are used to it. "

Southern People Weekly: In the early stages of treatment, what difficulties did you face?

CHIME: Too many. First of all, this disease is not quite the same as our SARS or bird flu in the past. Many times, SARS is a very serious illness of the patient. But some patients with new coronary disease early onset is not very dangerous, but late will suddenly an acceleration, the patient soon into a multi-organ failure state, will be an inflammatory storm. Once it's in this state, it's very difficult for our treatment to pull it back. This isn't like the old days. A lot of patients don't die of lung disease. Because we have ECMO, we have breathing, we have therapeutic strategies, we can replace lung function in patients. But many patients die from multiple organ failure outside the lungs, which is very different from the past.

Southern People Weekly: Why this sudden acceleration?

Bell ringing: On the surface, a storm of inflammation may be triggered in the patient's body, leading to the failure of various organs. What we've observed is that many patients have elevated markers of myocardial damage, so it's very likely that the virus itself can damage the heart muscle, similar to the symptoms of Myocarditis, which can damage many other organs.

Some of the patients we treated had other diseases, and when they got pneumonia, the disease got worse. For example, we have a patient who had an acute myocardial infarction, had a stent placed in his body, and when he developed pneumonia, there could be severe myocardial ischemia. The ones that come to us, they get worse in the general ward or in other hospitals, and they're all very, very critical.

Southern People Weekly: What does it mean to be very critical?

The BELL TOLLS: May Die at any moment.

Southern People Weekly: critically ill patients are most of the elderly?

Bell ringing: Most people are old, or have a lot of combined diseases. We have young people in our wards, as well as twenty somethings. But these young people are still in treatment, the death of patients have not yet very young.

Southern People: ECMO is the most powerful in vitro support system. How many patients can use ECMO?

Bell ringing: There are still a lot of ECMO devices available, but as I just said, not all critically ill patients can be saved by using ECMO. Many patients die outside the lungs, and multiple organ dysfunction syndrome is not an alternative to ECMO. If patients are in this state, ECMO can not save their lives.

Southern People Weekly: You have been fighting on the Wuhan Front for ten days. How is the patient's condition now?

Bell ringing: After 10 days of process optimization and team running-in, the number of deaths in the ward has been significantly reduced.

For example, an 83-year-old woman came in, was very dangerous, we give her oxygen is not good, we use the machine for non-invasive ventilation. After we adjusted her internal environment, adjusted her breathing parameters, avoided the Old Lady's tracheal intubation, and finally made the transition to a normal nasal cannula, where even her nucleic acid had turned negative, he's being transferred back to the general ward in the next two days. In our case, the patient was transferred to the General Ward and never returned, which means he was eventually discharged.

On the afternoon of February 2,37 patients with confirmed pneumonia were discharged from Wuhan's Covid-19, the highest number so far

People of the South: The temporary team, the temporary renovation of the ward, this will cause some difficulties in the work?

Bell ringing: There will be some difficulties at the beginning. Compared with the regular Icu Ward, the temporary renovation of the ICU ward is very cramped. There were four beds in one or two beds, along with a monitor, a suction machine, a dialysis machine and an ECMO. We have a lot of operations, the bed of a week to stand doctors and nurses, everyone against the wall against the corner, a lot of things are more difficult to operate than usual.

We didn't have a professional ICU nurse at the beginning, so it was extremely demanding. ICU nurses are highly specialized and must be familiar with critical care equipment, such as understanding what the vital signs on a monitor represent, understanding suction machines, and being able to load blood purification equipment, is Our double-pump dialysis machine and so on. And she should have a high degree of professional sensitivity to the changes in the patient's condition, and have a good cooperation with the doctor. ICU specialist nurses are hard to replace in a short period of time and are in short supply.

Now ICU nurses all over the country are gradually deployed to support, ICU nurses and non-ICU nurses cooperate with each other, one by one, running-in very well, the whole workflow in the standard up.

In this particular case, we have done a lot of running-in work, some difficulties you have not experienced, it is difficult to imagine. We have a lot of rules and regulations to try to adapt our work to the needs of this particular epidemic. For example, we can alternate things, do not let the examination at the same time, and some of the unified management of patients, reduce the amount of nurses walking, and so on. Now everyone's confidence has been restored, work efficiency has been higher, our equipment and processes have been step by step improvement. The team has worked together efficiently and coherently, and the work efficiency is much higher than before.

Southern People Weekly: What is your current working situation?

Bell ringing: the Doctor's Day shift is from 7:50 am to 5 pm. The nurses have night shift and day shift, but on average they stay for six or seven hours each, so every nurse comes out looking like she's collapsed because she's wearing a lot of clothes. Sometimes we have to carry the patient, and we have to turn the ninety kilos over completely. He's got so many tubes, he needs to flip the patient up and down. We wear a face screen, ventilation is very difficult, but also to do this intense physical work, all feel suffocated. And a lot of things are very difficult to do, not normal state can imagine.

ICU protection is the most strict, medical staff wearing a face screen, water vapor often get stuck in the eyes there, many times are not clear. For example, we go to ECMO, we usually only wear one layer of gloves, but now to wear three or even four layers of gloves, hand swelling in the operation, it will be a lot of difficulties.

Inside the ICU, the physical and energy requirements are very high, the gold and silver pool of work far beyond the intensity of our normal work.

Southern People Weekly: Do you now have to find some treatment of critically ill patients with pneumonia law?

Bell ringing: I have been summing up the data of our patients, but I don't have a good evidence, a scientific thing to answer you. It would be irresponsible to answer now. We're looking for a pattern, but I'm afraid we can't tell you what we found.

Southern People Weekly: Finally, we interviewed some mild or self-healing patients, people often feel very optimistic about the fever, this can be seen as a sign of improvement?

Bell ringing: You can't take it lightly. I don't have experience with mild cases, but we do have severe cases that get better and then get worse very quickly. I don't have enough experience with mild cases to give advice, but if you're quarantined at home, any symptoms of relapse or shortness of breath should be reported to the hospital.
